    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Long dining tables popular 16th-17th centuries, so-called because they resemble tables used in a refectory, although they were not necessarily actually used in a refectory. Typical examples are oblong tables with four or six turned legs that may be expanded by leaves.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000114707/Oxford English Dictionary Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051818/Coleridge, English Furniture and Cabinet-Makers, Burlington Magazine (1967)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000042061/Webster's Third New International Dictionary (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>通常用指十六至十七世紀間製造的長形餐桌，形式與食堂餐桌相仿，特指具有4或6條鏇製桌腿，且具折疊桌板的長方形餐桌。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lunghi tavoli da pranzo fatti nel XVI e il XVII secolo che ricordano quelli di un refettorio, in particolare per tavoli oblunghi con quattro o sei gambe che possono essere espanse dalle foglie.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Italian</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
